  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Lucretia Mott writes: &quot;That week in Boston, oh how pleasant!&quot; Lucretia Mott urges Maria Weston Chapman to visit her. Caroline Weston is gladly expected, and it is hoped that her sisters will come too. Lucretia Mott says: &quot;We shall open E. M. Davis&apos; house, &amp; can accomodate abolitionists--a score--.&quot; James Mott has written to William Lloyd Garrison respecting Loring Moody and W. W. Brown as agents for Pennsylvania. Lucretia Mott sends &quot;love unbounded to dear E. L. Follen. She must come while we feel so well acquainted with her, and seal an intimacy that promises us so much pleasure.&quot; Lucretia Mott refers to Mary G(ray Chapman)&apos;s long confinement to her sick room.</subfield>
